    <sec id="sec6">
      <title>Mitogenome assembly of eudicots</title>
      <p>To test the performance of PMAT, we first assembled the complete mitogenomes of eight eudicots using PMAT. Among them, four (<italic toggle="yes">A. thaliana</italic> Col-0, <italic toggle="yes">Cuscuta europaea</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">Helianthus annuus</italic> ANN1372â3, and <italic toggle="yes">Malus domestica</italic> Costard) were reassembled in this study and the other four (<italic toggle="yes">Amaranthus tricolor</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">Jasminum sambac</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">Populus trichocarpa</italic>, and <italic toggle="yes">Salix wilsonii</italic>) were <italic toggle="yes">de novo</italic> assembled for the first time (<xref rid="TB1" ref-type="table">Table 1</xref>). As shown in <xref rid="f2" ref-type="fig">Fig. 2</xref>, the average contig depths of chloroplast, mitochondrial, and nuclear genomes of each species were completely different, so the assembled contigs belonging to the mitogenome could be easily distinguished by their lengths and depths.</p>
